My apologies, I typed the recipe in such a rush there were some typos, here's the corrected recipe... A huge thank you to @misstamchiak who inspired my sea salt butter cookies... I tweaked her fantastic recipe slightly according to what I had in the kitchen... Here goes the recipe that makes about 50-60 mini melt-in-the mouth sea salt butter cookies:
- use a hand mixer to cream of room temperature softened 200g salted butter and 200g unsalted butter until the butter becomes pale and creamy
- add 80-100g of raw sugar that has been powdered in a food processor slowly to the creamed butter and continue to blend a bit at a time until all mixed
- double sift 100g of corn flour, 300g of plain flour and add slowly to the butter mixture using a spatula to fold until well mixed
- if you are hardworking, use a piping bag to pipe the cookie dough onto a baking tray lined with baking paper. If you are not so hard working, wet a spoon so the cookie dough doesn't stick to the spoon and just slap spoonfuls of dough onto a the baking paper lined tray. Leave about 1-2cm room between the cookies as the butter melts and the cookies with expand slightly.
- sprinkle a speck of Maldon sea salt on top of the cookie. You don't need a lot as the cookie will be slightly salty from the salted butter.
- preheat oven to 180 degrees and bake the cookies for about 15 minutes (depends on your oven)
- cool the cookies on a cooling rack
- enjoy the melt-in-the-mouth sea salt butter cookies inspired by Miss Tam Chiak!
